{ As previously said, White will most of the time be the one crashing through on the queenside.If you so choose, the diagrams can serve as exercises for training your positional judgment.Then the first question will always be: 'Who should be playing on the queenside?'The second question is the eternal 'How? Who is better and why?'Grandmasters have failed to take the right decision in those games, more than once.So it's an exciting challenge to compare yourself to those chess heroes ! }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Queenside Grind"]
[Black "Karpov, Anatoly vs. Short, Nigel D"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/ppp1b3/n2ppnqp/3P1pp1/2P2P2/2NN2P1/PP2P1BP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Let's be fair: most of the time grinds will come from White in this structure. Take this game }
1. b4
{ White isolates the knight on a6 for good and starts grabbing big chunks of space on the queenside. }
1... exd5 2. Nxd5 Nxd5 3. Bxd5+ Kh7 4. b5
{ Not best, as it lets the knight escape right away. Slow improvement, finishing development first was superior, considering the fact that Black as no clear plan  (notice the f4-pawn blocking any kind of kingside initiative)  . There was no real need to trade the poor black knight. }
4... Nc5 5. Nxc5 dxc5 6. Qc2
{ Despite his earlier inaccuracy White is still clearly for choice. } 6... a6
7. a4 Rb8 8. fxg5
{ Opening a second front, preparing to follow up with g4 when the time comes. }
8... hxg5 9. Ra3 c6 10. Bg2 Bf6 11. Be3 Bd4 12. Bxd4 cxd4 13. e3 dxe3 14. Rxe3
Be6 15. g4
{ In a good position, tactics always work. Black finally completed development but has too many weaknesses on the light squares. }
15... Rbe8 16. bxc6 bxc6 17. c5 Qf6 18. Bxc6 Rb8 19. gxf5 Bf7 20. Bg2 Rb2 21.
Qc3 Qxc3 22. Rxc3 Rd8 23. c6 Rdd2 24. Be4 Re2 25. c7 Rxe4 26. c8=Q
{ Doesn't look like Black had much fun, does it? } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Queenside Grind"]
[Black "Rabinovich, Ilya Leontievich vs. Ilyin Zhenevsky, Alexander"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1rbn1rk1/1pp3pp/p2pp3/3P1p2/2PN4/2R3P1/PP2PPBP/5RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ I'll drive the point home with a few more examples to either charm you into playing against this structure or warn you about its inherent pitfalls. Knowing what NOT to do is often a good starting point. }
1. c5
{ Black was about to prevent this charge with b6. Now the c-file falls into White's hands, profiting from delayed development. Obviously, Black is not going to offer kingside counterplay without queens on the board. }
1... e5 2. cxd6 cxd6 3. Nb3 { The queenside is easily invaded. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Queenside Grind"]
[Black "Botvinnik, Mikhail Moisevich vs. Ilyin Zhenevsky, Alexander"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/ppp1q1pp/2np1n2/4pp2/2PP4/2N2NP1/PP1QPPBP/R3R1K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nd5
{ A recurring move in similar structures, even with the Black pawn on f7 instead of f5. The c7 pawn is targeted in case of a trade on d5. }
1... Qd8 2. dxe5 dxe5 3. Rad1
{ White has excellent piece placement, so Black should try to create counterplay through }
3... e4 { but White can now target the e4 pawn after } 4. Ng5 Nxd5 5. Qxd5+
Qxd5 6. cxd5 Ne5 7. f3
{ The White knight is going to e6 and the light-squared bishop will dominate the Black knight. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Queenside Grind"]
[Black "Chekhover, Vitaly A vs. Budo, Alexander Semionovi"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "4rrk1/pbp1q1pp/1p1p4/4np2/1PP5/2Q2NP1/P2RPPBP/3R2K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ How do we play with White? } 1. c5
{ This position is, in fact, the tragedy of a tempo. Black to play would prevent this with Nd7 and follow up with f4 with a free, very dangerous initiative. Now White's central pressure is faster than Black's kingside tries. }
1... f4 2. Nxe5
{ Simplest: when your king is under fire trading pieces is often a clever strategy.  You only have to make sure you're not trading key defenders! }
2... Bxg2 3. cxd6 cxd6 { 19...Qxe5  20.Qxe5  Rxe5  21.d7 } 4. Nd3 f3 5. Qc4+
{ Nf4 is coming, securing the kingside. Next on the menu is the d6 pawn. } *

