[SetUp "1"]

1. a4
{ Compare the two bishops. Add to that White's more flexible structure, with levers on both sides of the board  (a5, g4, h5)  . You can now understand why he stands at least slightly better. }
1... Nf6
{ 22...cxd4  23.Nxd7  Rxd7  24.cxd4  Rdc7  25.Rxc7  Rxc7  26.Kf2  Rc3  27.Ke2  Black's control over the c-file is useless as he has no target. Meanwhile, the advantages previously cited still apply. }
2. Rcb1 { This procedure is always valuable against a a7-b6-c5 formation. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Queenside Grind"]
[Black "Kmoch, Hans vs. Kramer, Haije J"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "4r1k1/rbp3pp/1p1p2q1/p4p2/1PP1n3/P2QB1PB/4PP1P/R1R3K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. c5
{ Again, fast execution is key to prevent Black from growling on the other side.    23.Bf4  Qf6  24.f3  g5 ! }
1... dxc5 2. bxc5 f4 3. Bxf4 Nxc5 4. Qxg6 hxg6 5. Ra2
{ In this fight of 3 vs 1 against 4 vs 2 pawns, White is much better thanks to his bishops and the poor position of the a7 rook. Another general rule I have found useful is that in the case of asymmetric structures, the player with more pawns as his majority tends to stand better. }
