[White "Queenside Grind"]
[Black "Khasin, Abram Iosifovich vs. Simagin, Vladimir Pavlovich"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1r4rk/p5qp/3pp3/1b3p2/1P1P1Pnb/1Q1NPB2/P1R4P/5RBK w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. a4
{ Here again, Black has an open file next to the enemy king but no valid square to target. Hence the queenside majority rolls. There is not even a sliver of compensation for the previously invested pawn. }
1... Bd7
{ 27...Bxd3  28.Qxd3  Rxb4  29.d5 !  Crashing through in the center this time. Pawn fluidity is also a regular topic of discussion in the Classical Dutch Structure: he who rules pawns rules the board. }
2. b5
{ White is securing control of the two open files: g from g2 and c from c6. He's strategically winning. }
