[SetUp "1"]

{ As previously mentioned, Black is almost always the one that demolishes this part of the board. Get ready for some gore. White aficionado, have a light meal before going on: you will need blood sugar and a strong stomach for this. }
1... Qh5 2. Bc1 { Too slow. White wants to trade queens on g5. } 2... h6
{ More precise would have been to play Ba6 straight away, as then Qg5 is out of the question  (c4 being attacked)  . More to the point, taking on a5 is White's main source of counterplay, so he can never consider playing b5. }
3. Qd1
{ 22.bxa5!  Ba6!  23.Qc3  bxa5  24.a4!  Rf7  25.Ba3  Ref8  26.c5  Rf4!  27.Re3  dxc5  28.Rae1  R8f7  Somehow the computer manages to defend this as White, but I believe there are too many threats and ideas  (Nf6-g4, Rh4...)  to actually make it as a human being. For instance  29.Bxc5  Nxc5  30.Qxc5  Qh3  threatening  Rh4  (forces White to give up a piece on f3.) }
3... Re7 4. Be3 Bc8 5. Rc1 Ref7 6. c5 Nf6
{ This gives a lifeline to White, even though he would still have stood much worse. }
7. cxd6
{ 26.Bxf3  Ng4  27.Bxg4  Bxg4  28.Qd3  Bh3  29.Qe2  Bg4  30.Qd3  bxc5  31.bxc5  Bh3  32.Qe2  Qg6  33.Bd2  h5  This still is not pleasant at all. Possibly Black is winning in any case. }
7... Ng4 8. h4 g5 9. Rxc7 Rxc7 10. dxc7 gxh4 11. Bxf3 hxg3 12. Qe2 Qh2+ 13. Kf1
gxf2 14. Bxf2 Ba6 { You can't say I didn't warn you! } *

