{ Now, what for Black? } 1... b6
{ This uses the full board, getting to the kingside through challenging the center defended from the queenside. }
2. Qa4
{ An important notion in chess is that of 'Flipping the script': if you don't like the story your opponent has in store for you, grab a pen and make your own. White here is too affable.   31.Qxb6!  Bxa3  32.Rxc6  Rf6!  33.b4  is not clear at all, White has two pawns and huge activity for the invested bishop. }
2... c5 3. Qc6 Re6 4. Qxd5 Nf6 5. Qc4 Bxe5 6. dxe5 Ng4 7. Rc3 Qf7
{ With opposite-colored bishops, Black is in great shape thanks to his light-squared control through Bb7 and Nh2-f3 for instance. }
