[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/pbpn1ppp/1p1ppb2/8/2PP4/1PB2NP1/P1Q1PPBP/R4RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Since this structure is closed in nature, the heavy pieces will only give their full potential later in the game. Being in possession of the better light pieces is often key. This game illustrates perfectly why the trade of the White knight for Black light-squared bishop is highly favorable for White as a rule. }
1. Ng5 Bxg5 2. Bxb7 Rb8 3. Bc6
{ We need to compare the c6 bishop and the d7 knight. Despite the high number of pawns, usually in favor of the knight, it has no square to solidly land on. }
3... Qe7 4. b4 Rbd8 5. b5 Nb8 6. Be4 f5 7. Bg2 a5 8. f4
{ Now White opens up the center and takes advantage of his bishops. Look at that poor black knight! }
8... Bf6 9. e4 g6 10. Rae1 Qg7 11. e5 dxe5 12. fxe5
{ In principle, bishops act better in asymmetrical structures. } 12... Be7 13.
c5 Bg5 14. c6 { Now the black knight is effectively dead. } 14... h5 15. Qb3
Rfe8 16. d5 exd5 17. Bxd5+ Kh7 18. Bf7 Re7 19. e6 Bf6 20. Bxf6 Qxf6 21. Rd1 Rf8
22. Qd5 *

