[SetUp "1"]

{ What would you do as White? } 1. Bxf6
{ What matters when trading pieces is not the ones that leave but those that remain. The c3 bishop trades itself in order for White to get rid of both knights, after which Black's centre is severely weakened. Black will have to concede control of the nuclear squares  (e4,d4,e5,d5)  . }
1... Nxf6
{ 13...Qxf6  14.Nd2 !  d5  15.cxd5  exd5  16.Qb3 !  Tactics help strategy !  Be6   16...Nxd2  17.Qxd5+  Be6  18.Qxd2  is the small point.  17.Nf3  d5, e5 and d4 are all in White's possession : he's pressing.   13...Rxf6  14.Nd2 !  Nxd2   14...d5  15.cxd5  exd5  16.Nxe4  fxe4  17.Rad1  Black's d5 pawn is too weak, f3 will help White open the position against it. White is much better.  15.Qxd2  Bc6  16.Rad1  Ba4  17.Rc1  Bc6  18.Rc3  Preparing to double on the d-file. The d6 pawn is targeted and if Black plays e5 to protect it, then the d5 square is given to all of White's pieces.   13...gxf6  14.Nd2 !  Nxd2  15.Qxd2  Bc6  16.Rfd1  The d6 pawn is too weak. Black can continue with  Bxg2  17.Kxg2  Qc7  18.Qxd6  Qxc4  19.Rac1  Qe4+  20.Kg1  Where White has traded Black's weakness to activate all his pieces. White is dominating. }
2. Rad1 Qb6 3. Qd3 d5 4. Qd4
{ When you have a static advantage, trading will often favor you quite heavily, since it will reduce the opponent's counterplay, especially when a queen trade is involved. }
*

