{ In the Classical Dutch complex, the key light squares are d5, f5, e4, c4 and b5. Everything deeper into one of the players camps is only connected to occupying those squares. The e4-square has been granted its own chapter so the focus will shift from the centre to the wings here.If you so choose, the diagrams can serve as exercises for training your positional judgement.Then the first question will always be : "Who should play on the light squares ?"The second question is the eternal "How ? Who is better and why ?"Grandmasters have failed to take the right decision in those games, more than once.So it's an exciting challenge to compare yourself to those chess heroes ! }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Light square struggle"]
[Black "Reilly, Brian Patrick vs. Fine, Reuben"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q2k1/1p2brnp/p2pR1p1/2pPn3/2P1Bp2/2B3P1/PPQ2P1P/3NR1K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White to play and take the advantage. } 1. Bxe5 { Simple but efficient. }
1... dxe5 2. Nc3 { This is the important move. } 2... Nxe6 3. dxe6 Rg7 4. Bxb7
Rb8 5. Bg2
{ White has fantastic compensation, with the d5 square for his knight, the e6 pawn that he can defend with Bh3 and the absence of any structural defect on his side. He is much better. }
*

