{ The dark squares are well under control in the original situation of the Classical Dutch structure, as d6 and d4 patrol around c5 and e5. But this can easily change after the e5 break or more generally when one side decides to go forward with her pawns. Remember, weaknesses created are born but never die in those instances !If you so choose, the diagrams can serve as exercises for training your positional judgement.Then the first question will always be : "Who should be playing on the dark squares ?"The second question is the eternal "How ? Who is better and why ?"Grandmasters have failed to take the right decision in those games, more than once.So it's an exciting challenge to compare yourself to those chess heroes ! }
1. -- *

