[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The e4-square"]
[Black "The e4-square"]
[Result "*"]

{ The e4-square has been given its own chapter due to the massive amount of examples I had available, even after discarding more than half of them. When well executed, the e2-e4 break simply tears Black apart, but it also may result in Black occupying this very square after some trades. Knowing when a Black knight is well positioned on e4 is also crucial, as we started discussing in the Light Pieces chapter.If you so choose, the diagrams can serve as exercises for training your positional judgement.Then the first question will always be: "Who is in control of the e4 square right now ?"The second question is the eternal "Who is better and why ?"Grandmasters have failed to take the right decision in those games, more than once.So it's an exciting challenge to compare yourself to those chess heroes ! }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
