{ Second, we secure the e4 pawn to prepare f4. } 6. cxd5 cxd5 7. Qc5 Qd7
{ Third, we add the b6-Ba6 to d3 to the mix. Black is now winning. Granted White did not defend perfectly but he had the worse of it from the start nonetheless. A Black e4 against a White f4 usually gives this result. }
